	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=44274'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#FF00FF;'>d4rktala</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Apprentice<br>
			
				Posts: 13<br>
				
				Registered: 06-18-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=44274'>







<img src="/eq/i/icons/Races/high_elf.jpg" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Wizards&message.id=2900#M2900">1</a> of 24
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 705 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		
				background-color: #050A0E; 
				
				 background-image: none;
				 
				background-repeat: repeat-x;
				" 
			>
			Repost because other thread was locked<br><br>===<br><br>I'd love to see some implemented disciplines for Wizards. I think since we are the only caster class that specializes in damage with little to no utility, alot of changes for the better could be implemented by using our endurance bar. We should have multiple disicplines with reuse timers much like our rogue counterparts. This could easily be a great way to manage a multitude of problems that plagues the wizard class, such as overaggro, low DPS numbers, resistance problems, manapool concerns, death through summon issues.<br><br>Let's face it, we specialize in damage, and should have a myriad of ways to to quickly adjust when / how / where we implement that damage, outside of the realm of just our spell selection, as this is a largely limiting factor for us. Out class is so specialized in damage throughout our character's history, that we should have an ingame system to reflect that.<br><br>We should not have to pay an insane amount of AA's to get miniscule returns on how we can adjust the amount of damage that we can put out, all while having to rely on the resistance factors that have plagued our class for so long.<br><br>Frenzied Devastation was just the start of what a TRUE discipline lineup could do for us. Yet we settle for the insane recast timer on that &quot;discipline&quot;, with a huge side effect of double the cost of the spell. All while begging for a shorter recast timer on it, through a large AA cost.<br><br>Endurance for wizards is innately smaller then melee endurance and therefore, by nature reduces how often we could use these disciplines and would keep us out of the &quot;Melee&quot; realm of discing as we see fit. Again I think this could be a nice change for wizards and could offer us a nice change in how we play our damage focused class.<br><br>I would love to see some of the massive AA recommendations turned into discplines for wizards. 90 percent of the AA rec's that I see are specifically for increases DPS. I think it's time to implement a new system that allows us to better adjust that DPS, as we should truely be the masters of DD.<br><br>A million new ideas could open up before us with a system that has been proven to work for other &quot;damage&quot; based melee classes through use of their discipline, and has been proven to be programatically possible.<br><br>Feedback would be welcome. Thank you for your time.<br><br><br><br>The idea of disciplines was introduced due to the numbness of playing a melee class and just hitting attack, with little variation other then the discplines, which had a horrible system in place for using them. Melee saw the need to have there disciplines made &quot;reusable&quot; and on seperate timers, to help them combat the need to do something other then hit attack and continously reposition themselves. It also allows them to be more in &quot;control&quot; of there character, which the discpline system now provides with the short burst abilities they have, on different timers. Basically most disciplines are composed of:<br><br>Timer 1: offensive abiliities<br>Timer 2: defensive abilities<br>Timer 3: avoidance abilities<br>Timer 4: misc healing / pulling abilities<br><br>Each disc gives them the capability to lean more heavily to one side of there melee class, then to the other to help alleviate what was then, different and growing concerns of there respective classes. Rogues could avoid incoming damage, disc for higher burst damage, haste themselves, or even heal themselves with this new system.<br><br>The largest argument for this new system IMO was that it allowed them to be more in control of there current class, which is something I think we need in the Wizard class. Wizards in many regards are very much like melee prior to the implementation of the discipline timers. We are purely focused on one aspect of the game, damage. Much like rogues are for damage, much like warriors are for being front line damage absorbers, berserkers fell in line after the discipline system<br><br>Again, like I said before, the slow regeneration of endurance without any endurance &quot;buffers&quot; in the game currently, has it's own inherant system to keep what we can do with it in check, as compaired to melee with a much larger pool of endurance to draw from.<br><br><br>Shamans / druids already have a system being worked on, supposedly, that allows them greater versatility. Therefore, the comment that was made about caster classes have there versatility built into their spell selection falls to pieces. Especiallly since shamans and druids have some of the most versatile spell selections available to them. Where wizards spell selection is probably 95% dedicated to nothing but direct damage. Necromancers and mages have pets to assist with there damage output, plus both come with there own side abilities. Necromancers are absolutely one of the most versatile classes already. Magicians imo do need some help here as well but that's for them to decide.<br><br>I truely think that a discipline system could help wizards out with a great deal of the current problems that we are facing with the class today, in many respects, the same problems that plagued the melee class before the discipline system was invented, now plague the wizard class as well.<br><br><br>Just some simple ideas that could help alot for new disciplines.<br><br><br>30 - ResistantDuration 5 min<br>Reuse time from 60 (L30) to 30 (L60) minutes<br>Adds +3 to all resistances increasing to +10 at level 50+3 to all resistances increasing to +10 at 50th level. This discipline lasts for 5 minute, and has a base reuse time of 1 hour. The reuse time for this discipline will decrease as you level.<br><br>53 - Mana Barrier: 9 seconds.<br>Reuse time from 60 (L53) to 53 (L60) minutes<br><br>Creates a forceshield around your body that absorbs all incoming melee damage and lowers your hate equal to 1 point of hate per point of melee damage. Frontal attacks only<br><br>This discipline lasts for 9 seconds, and has a base reuse time of 60 minutes. The reuse time for this discipline will decrease as the wizard gains additional levels.<br><br><br>54 - Prismatic Burn: 14 seconds.<br>Reuse time from 30 (L54) to 24 (L60) minutes<br>When using this discipline, all spells will land for full damage with no resistance. This discipline lasts for 14 seconds, and has a base reuse time of 30 minutes. The reuse time for this discipline will decrease as the wizard gains additional levels.<br><br><br>55 - Planar Barrier: 12 seconds.<br><br>Reuse time from 30 (L55) to 25 (L60) minutes<br>Will automatically trigger when the wizard starts taking melee damage of any type. This discipline is triggered but remains inactive until the wizard starts to take melee damage. When triggered the wizards shield automatically reduces the amount of hate by 2000 points.This discipline lasts for 12 seconds, and has a base reuse time of 30 minutes. The reuse time for this discipline will decrease as the wizard gains additional levels.<br><br><br>57 - Hastened Destruction: 18 seconds<br>Reuse time from 30 (L57) to 27 (L60) minutes<br>Removes the recast wait time for all spells and lowers all spell cast times by 2 seconds, to a minimum of 1 .5 seconds of casting time. This discipline lasts for 18 seconds, and has a base reuse time of 30 minutes. The reuse time for this discipline will decrease as the wizard gains additional levels.<br><br><br>58 - Backlash: 15 seconds.<br>Reuse time from 30 (L58) to 28 (L60) minutes<br><br>Gives every direct damage spell the wizard casts the ability to backlash the target with extra spell damage. The backlash damage would be a percentage change equal to the chance to critical the spell, and would be at 1/2 the original spells damage. This backlash damage would be an instant effect on the target. . This discipline lasts for 15 seconds, and has a base reuse time of 30 minutes. The reuse time for this discipline will decrease as the wizard gains additional levels.<br><br>59 - Frenzied Devastation: 12 seconds<br>Reuse time from 30 (L59) to 29 (L60) minutes<br>As per AA, the more levels the wizard has, the less mana that is drained for the double mana cost. This discipline lasts for 12 seconds, and has a base reuse time of 30 minutes. The reuse time for this discipline will decrease as the wizard gains additional levels.<br><br><br>There's alot of work that could be done with disciplines for wizards.<br><br>The first thing I'd like to see, is us come together as a &quot;community&quot; to spell out what the 4 different discipline timers should entail and then decide what each timer should have specifically and then the different lengths of time for each of the individual discs themselves.<br><br>My idea would be:<br><br>Timer 1:<br>Offensive disciplines - Increased DPS<br><br>Timer 2:<br>Offensive discipline - Mana conservation<br><br>Timer 3:<br>Defensive discipline<br><br>Timer 4:<br>Hate reduction and Mana regeneration<br><br>Time 4 Mana regeneration could be very similiar to the health disciplines that melee get.<br><br>Anyway, I'd love to see some community support for this and a discussion detailing what each timer should be, if we stuck with the 4 base timers.<br><br>Since I'm a project manager, I could see something along this path for us to come together as a group of people looking to solve problems and go to Sony with solid justification of why we want these changes, the need for these changes, and how we would like to see these implemented.<br><br>The phased approach for something like this as a community could be:<br><br>Phase I<br>Discipline Styles<br>1) 2 weeks to Outline the 4 different styles of disciplines we would like<br>2) 3 days Vote on the popular opinions<br>3) Create a sticky thread with the results of the pole<br><br>Phase I Time: 2 weeks 3 days<br><br><br>Phase II<br>Discipline Outlines<br>1) 2 weeks Define the individual disciplines per discipline timer<br>2) 3 days Vote on popular opinions<br>3) Create sticky thread with results of the pole<br><br>Phase II Time: 2 weeks 3 days<br><br>Phase III<br>1) 2 weeks Define the reuse timers per discipline of each discipline that won the vote from Phase II<br>2) 3 days Vote on popular opinions<br>3) Create sticky thread with results of the pole<br><br>Phase III Time: 2 weeks 3 days<br><br>Phase IV<br>1) 2 weeks Work on the means of justification and provide supporting evidence of why we need the new disciplines<br><br>Phase IV Time: 2 weeks<br><br>Phase V:<br>1) Thread petition on our forums and on Sony forums, plus mounted email petitions from members of the community posting the need for these changes with a templated email created here on our forums. A push for change.<br><br>2) Continue to lobby Sony with the need for class change.<br><br>Phase V Time: Undetermined<br><br>Total Project Time up to lobby:<br><br>9 weeks 2 days<br><br><br>====<br><br><br>FYI this was combination of posts I made somewhere else, I just copy and pasted them all here<div></div>	
		</td></tr>
