		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			Seems to me that purchasing 300 more aa's to provide base flexibility for the class that continues to plague us is a bit unneccessary, I'm talking about changes that are necessary, not enhancements to the class.  Why bandaid it and cause a class to need 1200 aa's min to do their jobs.<br><br>Sorry but, endurance is not &quot;mana&quot; for melee. Endurance is a measure of how long you can exact different manuevers prior to becoming &quot;fatigued&quot;.  If that's the case then disciplines for melee only should go out the window as everyone has endurance.  The question at that point would be more along the lines of, which classes get more endurance.  A discipline system for casters could provide a TON of flexibility that is missing from the caster classes at this point.<br><br>To simply say casters shouldn't get disciplines because it's unfair, is heavily closedminded and shows nothing but an eager urge to keep options closed that could make the game funner for many people who find nuking nuking nuking nuking, MUCH LIKE, attack attack attack attack, mindnumbing.<br><br>Again, disciplines were created to allow more control of the character and give a less one dimensional view to the character.  A pitfall that wizards have had for a long time, since 95% of our focus, or more, is directed to damage.<br><br><span><br><blockquote><hr><span></span></blockquote></span><br><div></div>	
		</td></tr>
