<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=Wizards&message.id=2905#M2905">13</a> of 24
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 415 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<DIV>
<HR>
</DIV>
<DIV>d4rktala wrote:<BR>Seems to me that purchasing 300 more aa's to provide base flexibility for the class that continues to plague us is a bit unneccessary, I'm talking about changes that are necessary, not enhancements to the class.&nbsp; Why bandaid it and cause a class to need 1200 aa's min to do their jobs.</DIV>
<DIV>
<HR>
</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ff0000>Maybe you could elaborate on exactly what 1200 AA you "NEED" at a minimum of the total 1368 that your class gets to do your job. I don't know much about wizards, but as far as math goes, Offensively, all you would need is 550. Heck, 395 of your total AA's would be spent in trivial abilities not needed to effectly play in a group or raid.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>
<HR>
</DIV>
<DIV>Sorry but, endurance is not "mana" for melee. Endurance is a measure of how long you can exact different manuevers prior to becoming "fatigued".&nbsp; If that's the case then disciplines for melee only should go out the window as everyone has endurance.&nbsp; The question at that point would be more along the lines of, which classes get more endurance.&nbsp; A discipline system for casters could provide a TON of flexibility that is missing from the caster classes at this point.</DIV>
<DIV>
<HR>
</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ff0000>Endurance IS melee mana. Prior to Endurence was the Stamina bar which didtated movement and melee. Disciplines predate Endurence. When it was changed to Endurance, our disciplines were converted to use the Endurance instead of just being on long linked timers. The upside was that we could use another discipline right after using the first, the down side was that there was a cost. Endurance. These changes were put in place to balance Melee to the rest of the classes, not some zany gimic to take away from the tediousness of playing a melee. </FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>
<HR>
</DIV>
<DIV>To simply say casters shouldn't get disciplines because it's unfair, is heavily closedminded and shows nothing but an eager urge to keep options closed that could make the game funner for many people who find nuking nuking nuking nuking, MUCH LIKE, attack attack attack attack, mindnumbing.</DIV>
<DIV>
<HR>
</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ff0000>No one said it was unfair for casters to get Disciplines. It simple makes no sense. It's not about being close minded or cockblocking a class from having fun, it's about preserving balance. Wizards may be hurting, but Disciplines is neither the answer nor makes an ioda of sense.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>
<HR>
Again, disciplines were created to allow more control of the character and give a less one dimensional view to the character.&nbsp; A pitfall that wizards have had for a long time, since 95% of our focus, or more, is directed to damage.<SPAN>
<HR>
<SPAN></SPAN></DIV></SPAN></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<DIV><FONT color=#ff0000>Again, Disciplines are based on the physical side of a character, not mental. The cost of using those abilities is the loss of Endurance. The solution to your class's issue is not going to be found in a yellow bar.</FONT><BR></DIV>
<DIV></DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
