		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div>Nedrom...with full melee buffs (including champion) and a bard on AM I parsed 42 dps (note that is using a 750 damage proc weapon).  Regardless of any mana regen loss, meleeing as a caster is not a dps increase.</div><div> </div><div><font color="#ff0000">&quot;Endurance IS melee mana&quot;</font></div><div><font color="#ff0000"></font> </div><div>There have been many debates about this, and they are not equal.  Melee can dps w/o using endurance, casters can not.  Therefore these two ARE NOT equal.  Melee dps classes can regen the endurance lost on a disc by the time the disc is back up, excluding warriors who chain bellow and use cyclone blade.  Rogues and monks can sustain well in excess of 500 dps with 0 endurance, what dps does an oom caster produce? </div><div> </div><div>The problem we run into is our &quot;crit disc&quot; currently uses double the mana for a better chance to crit.  A rogue for example uses a crit disc and expends endurance, when that endurance is gone the rogue still can drop to their innate chance to crit for an endless duration.  When a wizard expends double their mana for a chance to do double the damage they more often then not end up blowing more mana to do less damage (as they spend 2x the mana for a normal nuke that didn't crit) then wind up oom quicker and then producing 0 damage. </div><div> </div><div>The point of the discipline he is wanting is basically to not penalize the mana pool for using the &quot;disc&quot;.  Basically you have your mana bar for normal casting but then to also have a power up type bar for discs.  Much like melee dps have their normal dps then their power bar (endurance bar) to go above and beyond their standard ability.  The endurance bar is already there so the assumption was to just use something that is already there.  If they changed the name of endurace to something different it would actually work universally for all classes.  Personally I think endurance is the wrong title since a melee can be out of endurance which means they should be too tired to do anything yet they continue doing their normal job without issue. </div>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
